Data Visualization¶

1) Commercial Loan interest Plot via ggplot

In [32]:
a <- ggplot(data=newdataframe)+geom_line(mapping=aes(x=Dates,y=commercialloaninterest),size=1)+
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=Dates,y=commercialloaninterest),size=5)
a+   geom_smooth(mapping=aes(x=Dates,y=commercialloaninterest),method = lm, color = "red")

`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

We can observe an increasing trend with fluctuations, smoothing line helps us to visualize the data.A abrupt increse in 2018 stems from change in Central Bank's policy. Also we can see the effect of the decision that reduce interest rates in 2020 due to COVID-19 pandemic.

2) Exchange Rates via ggplot

  a+   geom_smooth(mapping=aes(x=Dates,y=exchangerates),method = lm, color = "red")

`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

A obvious increasing trend can be seen.

Relations Between Data¶

1) Closed Joint Stock Companies and Commercial Loan Interest

In [38]:
scale2<-mean(newdataframe$closedjointstockcompanies)/mean(newdataframe$commercialloaninterest)

ggplot(data=newdataframe, aes(x=Dates))+geom_line(aes(y=closedjointstockcompanies),size=1.5,colour="red")+ geom_line(aes(y=commercialloaninterest*scale2))

In the plot , the black lines represent the commercial loan interest and the red line represents the closed joint stock companies. They both have incresing trends with increasing variance

2) Closed Joint Stock Companies and Unemployment Rate

In [39]:
scale2<-mean(newdataframe$closedjointstockcompanies)/mean(newdataframe$UnemploymentRate)

ggplot(data=newdataframe, aes(x=Dates))+geom_line(aes(y=closedjointstockcompanies),size=1.5,colour="red")+ geom_line(aes(y=UnemploymentRate*scale2))

The plot above displays plot of closed joint stock companies versus Unemployment Rate. As we can imagine, when the componies are closed unemployment rates increase and vice versa.

3) Closed Joint Stock Companies and Exchange Rate

In [40]:
scale2<-mean(newdataframe$closedjointstockcompanies)/mean(newdataframe$exchangerates)

ggplot(data=newdataframe, aes(x=Dates))+geom_line(aes(y=closedjointstockcompanies),size=1.5,colour="red")+ geom_line(aes(y=exchangerates*scale2))

We can observe positive correlation between these 2 datasets. Exchange rates effects companies in a bad way, as a result componies are closed.

In [44]:
alldata = read.xlsx("alldata.xlsx")
alldata$Dates = paste0(alldata$Dates, rep("-01",length(alldata$Dates))) 
alldata$Dates = as.Date(alldata$Dates)
alldata[,1]=as.Date(alldata[,1])
ggpairs(alldata,switch='both')

When we examine the ggpair plot, we can see that all datasets are correlated with "closed joint stock companies". They are all positively correlated which means when one of them increase, other increase.
